# 🐧 Linux File Viewing Commands

This chapter explains five important Linux commands used to view file content:

1. `cat` – Display complete file content
2. `head` – Display the beginning of a file
3. `tail` – Display the end of a file
4. `more` – View file content page by page
5. `less` – View and search large files interactively

These commands are very important for Production Support Analysts because application troubleshooting often starts with log files.

---

# 1. `cat` Command

## What is `cat`?

`cat` stands for **concatenate**.

It is commonly used to:

* Display file content
* Combine files
* Copy combined content into another file
* Add line numbers to displayed output
* Create small files using redirection

Think about opening a short notebook and reading all pages at once.

That is similar to:

```bash
cat file.txt
```

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
cat [OPTIONS] [FILE...]
```

---

## Display File Content

Suppose `student.txt` contains:

```text
Name: Ravi
Class: 5
School: ABC School
```

Run:

```bash
cat student.txt
```

Output:

```text
Name: Ravi
Class: 5
School: ABC School
```

---

## Display Multiple Files

Suppose:

`file1.txt`

```text
Apple
Mango
```

`file2.txt`

```text
Banana
Orange
```

Run:

```bash
cat file1.txt file2.txt
```

Output:

```text
Apple
Mango
Banana
Orange
```

`cat` reads the files in the order provided.

---

## `cat -n` – Show Line Numbers

```bash
cat -n application.log
```

Example:

```text
1 Application started
2 Database connected
3 Payment request received
4 ERROR: Connection timeout
```

This can help when discussing a specific line in a small file.

---

## `cat -b` – Number Non-Empty Lines

```bash
cat -b notes.txt
```

This numbers only non-empty lines.

Example file:

```text
Linux

SQL

Splunk
```

Output may look like:

```text
     1  Linux

     2  SQL

     3  Splunk
```

---

## `cat -s` – Squeeze Repeated Blank Lines

Suppose a file contains many empty lines.

Run:

```bash
cat -s notes.txt
```

Repeated blank lines are reduced to a single blank line in the displayed output.

The original file is not changed unless you explicitly redirect output somewhere.

---

## `cat -E` – Show End of Each Line

```bash
cat -E file.txt
```

Example:

```text
Linux$
SQL$
Splunk$
```

The `$` marks the end of each line.

This can help when investigating formatting problems.

---

## `cat -T` – Show Tab Characters

```bash
cat -T file.txt
```

Tab characters are displayed as:

```text
^I
```

This is useful when checking whether a file contains tabs instead of spaces.

---

## `cat -A` – Show Non-Printing Characters

```bash
cat -A file.txt
```

This can reveal characters such as tabs and line endings.

Useful for troubleshooting text-formatting problems.

---

## Combine Files into a New File

```bash
cat file1.txt file2.txt > combined.txt
```

Now:

```bash
cat combined.txt
```

may show:

```text
Apple
Mango
Banana
Orange
```

Important:

```text
>   Overwrite the destination file

>>  Append to the destination file
```

---

## Append File Content

```bash
cat new-errors.log >> all-errors.log
```

This appends the content of `new-errors.log` to `all-errors.log`.

Be careful with redirection because `>` can overwrite existing content.

---

## Create a Small File Using `cat`

```bash
cat > test.txt
```

Type:

```text
Linux Practice
Production Support
Log Analysis
```

Then press:

```text
Ctrl + D
```

`Ctrl + D` sends end-of-file input to the command.

Check:

```bash
cat test.txt
```

---

## Append Text Interactively

```bash
cat >> test.txt
```

Type more content and press:

```text
Ctrl + D
```

---

## Important `cat` Options

| Option | Purpose                            |
| ------ | ---------------------------------- |
| `-n`   | Number all output lines            |
| `-b`   | Number non-empty output lines      |
| `-s`   | Reduce repeated blank output lines |
| `-E`   | Show line endings                  |
| `-T`   | Show tabs                          |
| `-A`   | Show non-printing characters       |

---

## PSA Scenario – Read a Small Configuration File

Suppose you want to check a small configuration file:

```bash
cat /app/config/application.conf
```

For a small file, `cat` is simple and useful.

For a very large log file, avoid:

```bash
cat huge-application.log
```

because it can flood your terminal with thousands or millions of lines.

Use `less`, `head`, `tail`, or filtering commands instead.

---

# 2. `head` Command

## What is `head`?

`head` displays the beginning of a file.

By default, it displays the first **10 lines**.

Think of a 100-page book.

You only want to read the first few pages.

That is the idea behind `head`.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
head [OPTIONS] [FILE...]
```

---

## Display First 10 Lines

```bash
head application.log
```

By default, the first 10 lines are displayed.

---

## Display First 5 Lines

```bash
head -n 5 application.log
```

Short form:

```bash
head -5 application.log
```

Both are commonly seen.

For scripts and documentation, `-n 5` is often clearer.

---

## Display First 20 Lines

```bash
head -n 20 application.log
```

---

## Display First N Bytes

```bash
head -c 100 file.txt
```

This displays the first 100 bytes.

---

## Display Content Except the Last N Lines

GNU `head` supports a negative line count.

Example:

```bash
head -n -5 application.log
```

This displays all lines except the last 5.

Behavior and available options can vary across operating systems, so check:

```bash
head --help
```

or:

```bash
man head
```

---

## View Multiple Files

```bash
head file1.txt file2.txt
```

The output includes headers identifying each file.

---

## Important `head` Options

| Option | Purpose                                               |
| ------ | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| `-n N` | Show first N lines                                    |
| `-c N` | Show first N bytes                                    |
| `-q`   | Do not print file headers when reading multiple files |
| `-v`   | Always print file headers                             |

---

## PSA Scenario – Check Beginning of a Log File

Suppose you want to check application startup messages:

```bash
head -n 50 application.log
```

This may help you inspect:

* Application startup time
* Initial configuration loading
* Database connection setup
* Early startup errors

---

# 3. `tail` Command

## What is `tail`?

`tail` displays the end of a file.

By default, it displays the last **10 lines**.

This is one of the most important commands for Production Support.

Why?

Because new log messages are usually added near the end of a log file.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
tail [OPTIONS] [FILE...]
```

---

## Display Last 10 Lines

```bash
tail application.log
```

---

## Display Last 20 Lines

```bash
tail -n 20 application.log
```

Short form:

```bash
tail -20 application.log
```

---

## Display Last 100 Lines

```bash
tail -n 100 application.log
```

This is common during incident investigation.

---

## `tail -f` – Follow a Growing File

```bash
tail -f application.log
```

This keeps the command running and displays new lines as they are added to the file.

Example:

```text
INFO Application started
INFO Database connected
INFO User login request
ERROR Payment service timeout
```

If a new line is written:

```text
ERROR Database connection failed
```

it appears automatically.

Stop live monitoring using:

```text
Ctrl + C
```

---

## `tail -F` – Follow by File Name

```bash
tail -F application.log
```

`-F` is useful when log rotation may replace or recreate the file.

A simple difference:

```text
tail -f
→ Follows the opened file

tail -F
→ Keeps trying to follow the named file even if it is replaced or temporarily unavailable
```

This can be useful for rotating application logs.

---

## Start from a Specific Line

```bash
tail -n +50 file.txt
```

This means:

```text
Start displaying from line 50 onward
```

Example:

```bash
tail -n +100 application.log
```

---

## Display Last N Bytes

```bash
tail -c 100 file.txt
```

This displays the last 100 bytes.

---

## Follow Multiple Files

```bash
tail -f app.log error.log
```

`tail` identifies which file new output belongs to.

---

## Important `tail` Options

| Option | Purpose                       |
| ------ | ----------------------------- |
| `-n N` | Show last N lines             |
| `-c N` | Show last N bytes             |
| `-f`   | Follow new appended data      |
| `-F`   | Follow by file name and retry |
| `-q`   | Suppress file headers         |
| `-v`   | Always show file headers      |

---

## PSA Scenario – Live Log Monitoring

A user reports:

> Payment is failing now.

You identify the application log:

```bash
cd /app/logs
ls -ltr
```

Then:

```bash
tail -f payment.log
```

Ask for a controlled reproduction of the issue if your incident process allows it.

You may see:

```text
ERROR Payment request failed
ERROR Database timeout
ERROR Connection refused
```

The log message gives you a direction for further investigation.

Do not stop at the first `ERROR` line. Check surrounding context and timestamps.

---

## Useful Tail and Grep Combination

```bash
tail -n 500 application.log | grep "ERROR"
```

Case-insensitive search:

```bash
tail -n 500 application.log | grep -i "error"
```

Live filtering:

```bash
tail -f application.log | grep --line-buffered -i "error"
```

Note: `--line-buffered` is a GNU `grep` option and may not exist on every Unix-like system.

---

# 4. `more` Command

## What is `more`?

`more` displays file content one screen at a time.

Suppose a file has 10,000 lines.

Using:

```bash
cat large.log
```

will quickly print everything to the terminal.

Instead, use:

```bash
more large.log
```

This allows you to read the file page by page.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
more [OPTIONS] FILE
```

---

## Open a File

```bash
more application.log
```

---

## Important Keys Inside `more`

| Key     | Action                                   |
| ------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| `Space` | Next screen                              |
| `Enter` | Next line                                |
| `/word` | Search forward                           |
| `n`     | Repeat search                            |
| `q`     | Quit                                     |
| `h`     | Help, on implementations that support it |

Example search:

```text
/ERROR
```

Press Enter.

Then use:

```text
n
```

to find the next match.

---

## Start from a Specific Line

```bash
more +100 application.log
```

This starts viewing near line 100.

---

## Start from a Search Pattern

On common implementations:

```bash
more +/ERROR application.log
```

This starts near the first matching pattern.

---

## Important `more` Options

Common GNU/Linux options include:

| Option      | Purpose                                                 |
| ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| `-d`        | Display helpful prompts                                 |
| `-s`        | Squeeze repeated blank lines                            |
| `-N`        | Display line numbers on implementations that support it |
| `+N`        | Start near line N                                       |
| `+/pattern` | Start near a matching pattern                           |

Options differ between implementations. Use:

```bash
more --help
```

or:

```bash
man more
```

for your system.

---

## PSA Example

```bash
more application.log
```

Then search:

```text
/ERROR
```

This can work for manual log inspection, but `less` is usually more flexible.

---

# 5. `less` Command

## What is `less`?

`less` is an interactive file viewer.

It is generally better suited than `cat` for reading large text files.

You can:

* Move forward
* Move backward
* Search forward
* Search backward
* Jump to beginning
* Jump to end
* Follow growing files

A popular saying is:

```text
less is more
```

The meaning is that `less` provides more navigation features than the older `more` pager.

---

## Basic Syntax

```bash
less [OPTIONS] FILE
```

---

## Open a File

```bash
less application.log
```

---

## Important Keys Inside `less`

| Key        | Action                                    |
| ---------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| `Space`    | Next page                                 |
| `b`        | Previous page                             |
| `Enter`    | Next line                                 |
| `↑`        | Move up                                   |
| `↓`        | Move down                                 |
| `g`        | Go to beginning                           |
| `G`        | Go to end                                 |
| `/word`    | Search forward                            |
| `?word`    | Search backward                           |
| `n`        | Next search match                         |
| `N`        | Previous search match                     |
| `F`        | Follow new data                           |
| `Ctrl + C` | Stop follow mode and return to navigation |
| `q`        | Quit                                      |

---

## Search for ERROR

Open:

```bash
less application.log
```

Inside `less`, type:

```text
/ERROR
```

Press Enter.

Then:

```text
n
```

moves to the next match.

```text
N
```

moves to the previous match.

---

## Search Backward

Inside `less`:

```text
?ERROR
```

This searches backward.

---

## Open Near the End of a File

```bash
less +G application.log
```

This opens the file and moves near the end.

---

## Follow a Growing File

Open:

```bash
less application.log
```

Then press:

```text
Shift + F
```

or simply:

```text
F
```

New lines are displayed as the file grows.

Press:

```text
Ctrl + C
```

to stop follow mode and return to normal navigation.

Then press:

```text
q
```

to quit.

---

## Show Line Numbers

```bash
less -N application.log
```

This displays line numbers.

---

## Do Not Wrap Long Lines

```bash
less -S application.log
```

Long lines are chopped instead of wrapped.

This can be useful for wide structured logs.

---

## Ignore Case in Searches

```bash
less -i application.log
```

This makes searches ignore case when the search pattern itself contains no uppercase letters.

---

## Important `less` Options

| Option | Purpose                                                   |
| ------ | --------------------------------------------------------- |
| `-N`   | Show line numbers                                         |
| `-S`   | Chop long lines                                           |
| `-i`   | Smart case-insensitive search                             |
| `-X`   | Do not clear the screen on exit on common implementations |
| `+G`   | Start near the end of the file                            |

---

# `cat` vs `head` vs `tail` vs `more` vs `less`

| Command   | Main Purpose                      | Best Use                            |
| --------- | --------------------------------- | ----------------------------------- |
| `cat`     | Display complete content          | Small files                         |
| `head`    | Display beginning                 | First lines and startup information |
| `tail`    | Display end                       | Recent log entries                  |
| `tail -f` | Follow new lines                  | Live log monitoring                 |
| `more`    | Page-by-page viewing              | Basic sequential reading            |
| `less`    | Interactive navigation and search | Large files and logs                |

